[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 7.5: 30-Day Readmission Risk
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Medium · **Phase:** Growth · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.003 per discharge scored
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A patient gets discharged from the hospital on a Thursday afternoon. They're handed a stack of papers: medication instructions, follow-up appointment reminders, dietary guidelines, wound care protocols. They nod along, sign the discharge form, and go home. Two weeks later, they're back in the ED with the same condition, or a complication of it, or something that could have been caught with a single phone call from a nurse.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the 30-day readmission problem, and it is one of the most studied, most measured, and most financially punishing quality metrics in American healthcare.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CMS penalizes hospitals for excess readmissions through the Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program (HRRP). The penalties are real: up to 3% of total Medicare reimbursement, applied across all Medicare discharges, not just the readmitted ones. For a mid-size hospital doing $200M in Medicare revenue, that's up to $6M at stake annually. The program covers heart failure, AMI, pneumonia, COPD, hip/knee replacement, and CABG. And the penalty calculation compares your readmission rate against a risk-adjusted expected rate, so you can't game it by simply avoiding sick patients.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m But the financial penalty is almost secondary to the human cost. A readmission usually means something went wrong in the transition of care. The patient didn't understand their medications. They couldn't get to their follow-up appointment. Their home environment wasn't safe for recovery. They developed a complication that nobody was monitoring for. These are preventable failures, and they happen at scale: roughly 15-20% of Medicare patients are readmitted within 30 days of discharge.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The good news: targeted post-discharge interventions work. Transition care programs, nurse follow-up calls, medication reconciliation, home health visits, remote patient monitoring. These programs reduce readmissions by 20-40% when applied to the right patients. The key phrase there is "the right patients." These interventions are expensive. You can't give every discharged patient a dedicated care transition nurse. You need to know who is most likely to bounce back, so you can focus your limited resources where they'll have the most impact.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m That's the prediction problem. Score every patient at discharge. Identify the high-risk ones. Route them to the appropriate intervention. Measure whether it worked.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Predicting Who Comes Back
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Readmission Prediction as a Time-Bounded Classification Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m At its core, 30-day readmission prediction is binary classification with a fixed time horizon: will this patient be readmitted to any acute care hospital within 30 days of discharge? Yes or no. You train on historical discharge records where you know the outcome, then apply the model to new discharges in real time (or near-real-time) to generate risk scores.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The 30-day window is not arbitrary. It's the CMS measurement window for HRRP penalties. Some organizations also track 7-day and 90-day readmissions, but 30-day is the regulatory standard and the most common prediction target.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This sounds like a straightforward supervised learning problem. And conceptually, it is. But the details are where it gets interesting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Makes This Harder Than It Looks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The base rate problem.** Overall 30-day readmission rates hover around 15-20% for Medicare populations, lower for commercial. That means your positive class is the minority. A model that predicts "no readmission" for everyone achieves 80-85% accuracy. Useless, but it looks good on a slide. You need metrics that account for class imbalance: AUC-ROC, precision-recall curves, and calibration plots. The C-statistic (equivalent to AUC) for most published readmission models falls between 0.60 and 0.75. That's meaningfully better than chance, but it's not the 0.95+ AUC you see in image classification papers. This is a hard prediction problem with inherent irreducible uncertainty.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The information availability problem.** The most useful time to generate a readmission risk score is at discharge, because that's when you can still intervene (schedule follow-up, arrange home health, activate a care transition program). But at discharge, you don't yet have post-discharge data: did the patient fill their prescriptions? Did they make it to their follow-up? Are they eating properly? The factors that most directly cause readmissions are often post-discharge behaviors that you can't observe at prediction time. You're predicting with incomplete information by design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The social determinant gap.** Clinical data (diagnoses, procedures, lab values, medications) is readily available in the EHR. Social determinants of health (housing stability, food security, transportation access, social isolation, health literacy) are powerful predictors of readmission but are rarely captured in structured form. A patient who lives alone, can't drive, and doesn't fully understand their discharge instructions is at dramatically higher risk than their clinical profile alone would suggest. Most models underperform on this axis because the data simply isn't there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The "planned" vs. "unplanned" distinction.** Not all readmissions are bad. A patient discharged after a staging procedure who returns for their planned surgery is technically a readmission, but it's not a quality failure. CMS excludes planned readmissions from penalty calculations using a complex algorithm. Your prediction model needs to target unplanned readmissions specifically, which means your training labels need to apply the same exclusion logic.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Case mix variation.** A hospital that treats sicker patients will naturally have higher readmission rates. CMS accounts for this through risk adjustment (comparing your observed rate against an expected rate given your patient mix). Your internal prediction model needs to be useful for operational decisions (who gets the intervention), not just for reporting. That means raw probability matters more than relative ranking.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Feature Categories That Drive Predictions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The features that predict 30-day readmission cluster into several domains:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Index admission characteristics.** Length of stay, admission source (ED vs. elective vs. transfer), discharge disposition (home vs. SNF vs. home health), primary diagnosis, procedure codes, ICU days, number of consultants involved. Longer stays and ICU involvement signal complexity. Discharge to home without services for a complex patient is a red flag.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical severity indicators.** Lab values at discharge (albumin, BNP, creatinine, hemoglobin), vital sign trends, number of active diagnoses, Elixhauser or Charlson comorbidity indices, medication count at discharge. Patients discharged with abnormal labs or on 10+ medications are higher risk.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior utilization history.** Number of hospitalizations in the past 6-12 months, ED visits, prior 30-day readmissions. Past behavior is the single strongest predictor of future behavior. A patient with three admissions in the last six months is almost certainly coming back.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication complexity.** Number of discharge medications, number of medication changes during the stay, high-risk medications (anticoagulants, insulin, opioids), polypharmacy indicators. Medication errors and non-adherence are leading causes of preventable readmissions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Functional and social factors.** When available: living situation, mobility status, cognitive status, caregiver availability, insurance type (as a proxy for access), zip code-level deprivation indices. These are often the most predictive features but the hardest to capture systematically.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Discharge process indicators.** Whether a follow-up appointment was scheduled before discharge, whether medication reconciliation was completed, whether discharge education was documented, time of day and day of week of discharge (Friday afternoon discharges have worse outcomes because follow-up resources are unavailable over the weekend).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Model Approaches: What Works
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **LACE and HOSPITAL scores.** These are simple, validated point-based scoring systems that use a handful of variables (Length of stay, Acuity of admission, Comorbidities, ED visits in prior 6 months for LACE). They're easy to implement, require no ML infrastructure, and provide a reasonable baseline. Their C-statistics typically fall in the 0.60-0.68 range. They're a good starting point but leave significant predictive power on the table.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Gradient boosted trees (XGBoost, LightGBM).** The workhorse of tabular healthcare prediction. These models handle mixed feature types, missing values, and non-linear interactions naturally. With a well-engineered feature set, they typically achieve C-statistics of 0.68-0.75 for 30-day readmission. They also produce feature importance scores, which helps with clinical interpretability and intervention targeting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Deep learning on event sequences.** Recurrent neural networks or transformers trained on the full sequence of clinical events (diagnoses, procedures, medications, labs over time) can capture temporal patterns that point-in-time features miss. These approaches show promise in research settings but require substantially more data, engineering effort, and compute. For most hospital systems, gradient boosting on well-engineered features is the practical sweet spot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Ensemble approaches.** Combining a clinical rules-based score (like LACE) with a machine learning model often outperforms either alone. The rules capture known clinical risk factors; the ML model captures subtle patterns in the data that clinicians haven't codified. A simple weighted average or stacking approach works well.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Calibration: The Most Underrated Requirement
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For readmission prediction, calibration is arguably more important than discrimination. Here's why: your care transition team has finite capacity. If you tell them "these 50 patients are high-risk," they need to trust that those patients genuinely have elevated risk. If your model says "40% readmission probability" but the actual rate for that group is 20%, you're wasting half your intervention capacity on patients who would have been fine anyway.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Calibration means that predicted probabilities match observed frequencies. Platt scaling or isotonic regression applied after model training can fix calibration without sacrificing discrimination. Always check calibration plots stratified by key subgroups (diagnosis category, age, race) because a model can be well-calibrated overall but poorly calibrated for specific populations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Fairness and Bias Considerations
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Readmission risk models trained on historical data will encode existing disparities. Patients from disadvantaged communities have higher readmission rates partly because of worse post-discharge support systems (fewer pharmacies, less transportation, fewer follow-up options). A model that accurately predicts this disparity might seem "fair" in a statistical sense, but using it to allocate interventions could either help (directing more resources to disadvantaged patients) or harm (if high-risk scores are used punitively or to avoid admitting certain patients).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The ethical framing matters: are you using the score to help high-risk patients get more support, or to penalize them? The same model can serve either purpose depending on how the score is operationalized. Be explicit about this in your implementation design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The readmission risk pipeline has five logical stages:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Discharge Event Detection] → [Feature Assembly] → [Model Scoring] → [Risk Stratification] → [Intervention Routing]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Discharge Event Detection.** The pipeline triggers when a patient is discharged from an inpatient stay. This requires integration with the hospital's ADT (Admit-Discharge-Transfer) system, typically via HL7 or FHIR event feeds. The trigger must distinguish inpatient discharges from observation stays, ED visits, and outpatient procedures. Timing matters: you want the score available within hours of discharge, not days.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feature Assembly.** Pull the relevant data for the discharged patient from available source systems: EHR (diagnoses, procedures, labs, medications, vitals), claims history (prior utilization), ADT history (prior admissions, ED visits), and any available social/demographic data. Assemble these into the feature vector the model expects. This step often involves real-time queries against multiple systems, which makes it the most architecturally complex piece.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Model Scoring.** Pass the assembled feature vector through the trained model to produce a readmission probability. This should be a low-latency operation (sub-second for a single patient). The model itself is trained offline on historical data and deployed as a scoring endpoint. Retraining happens on a schedule (monthly or quarterly) as new outcome data accumulates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Risk Stratification.** Convert the raw probability into an actionable tier (high, medium, low) based on thresholds calibrated to your intervention capacity and cost-effectiveness analysis. A common approach: top 15% = high risk (intensive intervention), next 25% = medium risk (standard follow-up), remainder = low risk (routine discharge). The thresholds should be adjustable as your care transition team's capacity changes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Intervention Routing.** Based on the risk tier and the contributing risk factors, route the patient to the appropriate post-discharge program. High-risk heart failure patients might get a home health referral and daily telemonitoring. High-risk patients with medication complexity might get a pharmacist-led medication reconciliation call. The routing logic sits on top of the model and translates predictions into actions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The feedback loop: track 30-day outcomes for all scored patients. Compare predicted vs. actual readmission rates by risk tier. Monitor for model drift (changing patient populations, new care patterns, coding changes). Retrain when performance degrades below acceptable thresholds.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for model training and real-time inference.** Readmission scoring needs to happen within hours of discharge, which means you need a model endpoint that can score individual patients on demand. SageMaker provides managed real-time endpoints with auto-scaling, plus the training infrastructure for periodic model retraining. The built-in XGBoost container is well-suited for the gradient boosted tree approach that dominates this problem space.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon HealthLake for clinical data aggregation.** HealthLake provides a FHIR-native data store that can ingest clinical data from EHR systems and normalize it into a queryable format. For readmission prediction, you need to pull together diagnoses, procedures, medications, labs, and encounter history for each patient at discharge time. HealthLake's FHIR search capabilities make this feature assembly step cleaner than querying raw EHR databases directly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Glue for feature engineering pipelines.** The batch feature engineering (computing rolling utilization metrics, comorbidity indices, medication complexity scores) runs as scheduled ETL jobs. Glue handles the heavy transformations on historical data that feed model training, while real-time features are assembled at scoring time from HealthLake queries.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon EventBridge for discharge event processing.** ADT discharge events flow into EventBridge, which triggers the scoring pipeline. EventBridge's event filtering ensures only qualifying inpatient discharges (not observation stays or planned returns) trigger the model. This event-driven architecture means scores are generated automatically without manual intervention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions for pipeline orchestration.** The scoring workflow (detect discharge, assemble features, invoke model, stratify risk, route intervention, store results) has multiple steps with error handling and retry logic. Step Functions coordinates this sequence and provides visibility into failures. If the feature assembly step fails (e.g., a source system is down), the workflow retries with backoff rather than silently dropping the patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for risk score storage and lookup.** Scored patients need their risk tier accessible to downstream systems (care management platforms, EHR dashboards, nurse worklists) in real time. DynamoDB provides single-digit-millisecond lookups by patient ID. Scores are written at discharge and read by operational systems throughout the 30-day window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SNS for intervention notifications.** When a patient is scored as high-risk, the appropriate care team needs to be notified immediately. SNS delivers notifications to care transition nurses, case managers, or automated workflow systems based on the risk tier and contributing factors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Data Sources
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         A[ADT Feed\nHL7/FHIR]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         B[EHR Clinical Data]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         C[Claims History]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         D[Lab Results]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         E[Pharmacy Data]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Event Processing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         A -->|Discharge Event| F[EventBridge\nDischarge Filter]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         F -->|Qualified Discharge| G[Step Functions\nScoring Workflow]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Feature Assembly
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         G -->|Query Patient Data| H[HealthLake\nFHIR Store]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         G -->|Historical Features| I[S3 Feature Store\nParquet]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         H --> J[Feature Vector\nAssembly]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         I --> J
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Model Scoring
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         J -->|Feature Vector| K[SageMaker Endpoint\nXGBoost Model]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         K -->|Probability| L[Risk Stratification\nLambda]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Action
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         L -->|High Risk| M[SNS\nCare Team Alert]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         L -->|All Scores| N[DynamoDB\nRisk Score Store]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         L -->|Dashboard| O[QuickSight\nReadmission Analytics]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Model Lifecycle
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         P[Glue\nFeature Engineering] -->|Training Data| Q[S3\nTraining Dataset]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Q --> R[SageMaker Training\nMonthly Retrain]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         R -->|New Model| K
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style K fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style N fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon HealthLake, AWS Glue, Amazon EventBridge, AWS Step Functions, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon SNS, Amazon S3, Amazon QuickSight |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `healthlake:SearchWithGet`, `healthlake:ReadResource`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `sns:Publish`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `states:StartExecution` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | Required. All services handling PHI must be covered under your AWS BAA. HealthLake, SageMaker, DynamoDB, S3, Glue, Step Functions, EventBridge, SNS, and QuickSight are all HIPAA-eligible. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for feature stores and model artifacts. DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default). HealthLake: AWS-managed or customer-managed KMS keys. SageMaker: KMS encryption for training data, model artifacts, and endpoint traffic. All inter-service communication over TLS. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: SageMaker endpoints, Glue jobs, and Lambda functions in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, SageMaker Runtime, and CloudWatch Logs. HealthLake accessed via VPC endpoint. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all API calls. Critical for HIPAA audit trail: who accessed which patient's risk score, when, and from where. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | MIMIC-III or MIMIC-IV (publicly available ICU dataset with readmission outcomes). CMS Synthetic Public Use Files for claims-based features. Never use real PHI in development. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | SageMaker real-time endpoint (ml.m5.large): ~$0.115/hour (~$83/month). Scoring latency: <200ms per patient. At 100 discharges/day, the per-discharge cost is ~$0.003. HealthLake: $0.60/GB stored + $0.09 per 1000 read operations. Glue: $0.44/DPU-hour for batch feature engineering. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Model training (monthly), real-time scoring endpoint, model registry |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon HealthLake** | FHIR-native clinical data store for real-time feature queries |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Glue** | Batch feature engineering, historical feature computation, training data preparation |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Discharge event ingestion and filtering |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates the scoring workflow with error handling and retries |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores risk scores for real-time lookup by downstream systems |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SNS** | Delivers high-risk alerts to care transition teams |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Feature store (Parquet), model artifacts, training datasets, scoring audit logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Readmission analytics dashboards for leadership and quality teams |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all PHI-containing stores |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitoring, alerting on scoring failures, model performance metrics |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample repos demonstrate patterns used in this recipe:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-healthlake-server-cdk`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-healthlake-server-cdk): CDK constructs for deploying HealthLake with proper security configuration
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-sagemaker-examples`](https://github.com/aws/amazon-sagemaker-examples): SageMaker training and deployment patterns including XGBoost for healthcare use cases
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 1: Discharge Event Detection and Filtering
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **What this does:** Listens for ADT discharge events and filters to only qualified inpatient discharges that should be scored. Observation stays, planned readmissions, and transfers to other acute facilities are excluded.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **What goes wrong if you skip it:** You score patients who shouldn't be scored (observation stays aren't subject to readmission penalties), waste compute on irrelevant events, and pollute your outcome tracking with non-qualifying encounters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION handle_discharge_event(event):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Parse the ADT message (HL7 A03 or FHIR Encounter update)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     patient_id = event.patient_identifier
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     encounter_type = event.encounter_class
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     discharge_disposition = event.disposition
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     length_of_stay = event.discharge_date - event.admit_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Filter: only score qualifying inpatient discharges
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF encounter_type NOT IN ["inpatient", "acute"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         LOG "Skipping non-inpatient encounter for patient {patient_id}"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN null
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Exclude transfers to other acute facilities (not true discharges)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF discharge_disposition IN ["transfer_acute", "left_ama"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         LOG "Skipping transfer/AMA for patient {patient_id}"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN null
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Exclude very short stays (likely observation misclassified)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF length_of_stay < 1 day:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         LOG "Skipping sub-24hr stay for patient {patient_id}"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN null
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Qualified discharge: trigger scoring workflow
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id: patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         encounter_id: event.encounter_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         discharge_date: event.discharge_date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         primary_diagnosis: event.primary_diagnosis,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         discharge_disposition: discharge_disposition
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 2: Feature Assembly from Clinical Data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **What this does:** Queries multiple data sources to assemble the complete feature vector for the discharged patient. Combines real-time clinical data from the current encounter with historical utilization patterns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **What goes wrong if you skip it:** The model receives incomplete or stale data, producing unreliable risk scores. Missing features (especially prior utilization history) dramatically reduce predictive accuracy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION assemble_features(discharge_info):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     patient_id = discharge_info.patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     encounter_id = discharge_info.encounter_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Current Encounter Features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Query HealthLake for the index admission details
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     encounter = FHIR_SEARCH("Encounter", id=encounter_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     conditions = FHIR_SEARCH("Condition", encounter=encounter_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     medications = FHIR_SEARCH("MedicationRequest", encounter=encounter_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     labs = FHIR_SEARCH("Observation", encounter=encounter_id, category="laboratory")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     procedures = FHIR_SEARCH("Procedure", encounter=encounter_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     current_features = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         length_of_stay: encounter.length_of_stay_days,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         admission_source: encounter.admission_source,  // ED, elective, transfer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         discharge_disposition: encounter.discharge_disposition,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         primary_diagnosis_code: encounter.primary_diagnosis.icd10,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         diagnosis_count: COUNT(conditions),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         procedure_count: COUNT(procedures),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         icu_days: calculate_icu_days(encounter),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         discharge_medication_count: COUNT(medications WHERE status="active"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         high_risk_medications: COUNT(medications WHERE code IN HIGH_RISK_MED_LIST),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Lab values at discharge (most recent)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         albumin_last: most_recent_value(labs, code="1751-7"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         creatinine_last: most_recent_value(labs, code="2160-0"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         hemoglobin_last: most_recent_value(labs, code="718-7"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sodium_last: most_recent_value(labs, code="2951-2"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bnp_last: most_recent_value(labs, code="42637-9")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Historical Utilization Features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Look back 12 months for prior utilization patterns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     lookback_start = discharge_info.discharge_date - 365 days
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     prior_encounters = FHIR_SEARCH("Encounter",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient=patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         date_range=[lookback_start, discharge_info.discharge_date],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         type="inpatient")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     prior_ed_visits = FHIR_SEARCH("Encounter",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient=patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         date_range=[lookback_start, discharge_info.discharge_date],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         type="emergency")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     history_features = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         admissions_past_6mo: COUNT(prior_encounters WHERE date > now - 180 days),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         admissions_past_12mo: COUNT(prior_encounters),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ed_visits_past_6mo: COUNT(prior_ed_visits WHERE date > now - 180 days),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         prior_30day_readmission: ANY(prior_encounters WHERE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             days_since_prior_discharge <= 30),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         days_since_last_admission: days_between(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             most_recent(prior_encounters).discharge_date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             discharge_info.discharge_date)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Comorbidity Features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Calculate Elixhauser comorbidity index from all active conditions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     all_conditions = FHIR_SEARCH("Condition", patient=patient_id, status="active")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     comorbidity_features = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         elixhauser_score: calculate_elixhauser(all_conditions),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         has_chf: any_condition_in_group(all_conditions, "CHF"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         has_diabetes: any_condition_in_group(all_conditions, "DIABETES"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         has_copd: any_condition_in_group(all_conditions, "COPD"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         has_ckd: any_condition_in_group(all_conditions, "CKD"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         has_depression: any_condition_in_group(all_conditions, "DEPRESSION"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_chronic_conditions: COUNT(all_conditions WHERE category="chronic")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Demographic Features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     patient = FHIR_SEARCH("Patient", id=patient_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     demographic_features = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         age: calculate_age(patient.birth_date),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sex: patient.gender,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         insurance_type: patient.coverage_type,  // Medicare, Medicaid, Commercial
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         zip_deprivation_index: lookup_adi(patient.address.postal_code)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Combine all feature groups into single vector
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN merge(current_features, history_features,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                  comorbidity_features, demographic_features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 3: Model Scoring
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **What this does:** Passes the assembled feature vector to the trained XGBoost model and returns a readmission probability between 0 and 1.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **What goes wrong if you skip it:** Obviously you don't get a risk score. But more subtly, if you skip the preprocessing and validation step, you'll send malformed features to the model and get garbage predictions without any error signal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION score_patient(feature_vector):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Validate feature completeness
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     required_features = ["length_of_stay", "admissions_past_6mo",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                          "elixhauser_score", "age", "discharge_medication_count"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     missing = [f FOR f IN required_features IF feature_vector[f] IS NULL]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF COUNT(missing) > 2:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         LOG_WARNING "Too many missing features for patient, using fallback score"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN {probability: null, method: "insufficient_data", missing: missing}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Handle missing values (model expects specific sentinel values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each feature IN feature_vector:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF feature.value IS NULL:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             feature.value = -999  // XGBoost handles this as missing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Invoke the SageMaker endpoint
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = SAGEMAKER_INVOKE(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         endpoint_name = "readmission-risk-v2",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         content_type = "text/csv",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         body = feature_vector_to_csv(feature_vector)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     raw_probability = PARSE_FLOAT(response.body)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply calibration (Platt scaling learned during training)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     calibrated_probability = platt_scale(raw_probability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         A = CALIBRATION_PARAMS.A,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         B = CALIBRATION_PARAMS.B)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         probability: calibrated_probability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         raw_score: raw_probability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         method: "xgboost_v2",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model_version: response.model_version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         scored_at: NOW()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 4: Risk Stratification and Intervention Routing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **What this does:** Converts the raw probability into an actionable risk tier and determines which intervention pathway the patient should receive based on their risk level and contributing factors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **What goes wrong if you skip it:** A probability of 0.42 means nothing to a care transition nurse. They need "high risk, prioritize for home health referral." Without stratification and routing, the model output sits in a database and nobody acts on it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION stratify_and_route(score_result, feature_vector, discharge_info):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     probability = score_result.probability
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Stratify into tiers based on calibrated thresholds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Thresholds are set based on intervention capacity and cost-effectiveness
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF probability >= 0.35:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         risk_tier = "HIGH"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         intervention_level = "intensive"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF probability >= 0.20:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         risk_tier = "MEDIUM"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         intervention_level = "standard"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         risk_tier = "LOW"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         intervention_level = "routine"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Determine primary risk drivers for intervention targeting
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // (from model feature importance for this specific patient)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     risk_drivers = get_top_contributing_features(feature_vector, top_n=5)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Route to appropriate intervention based on tier + drivers
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     interventions = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF risk_tier == "HIGH":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // All high-risk patients get a nurse follow-up call within 48 hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         interventions.ADD("nurse_callback_48hr")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Specific interventions based on risk drivers
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF "discharge_medication_count" IN risk_drivers OR
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m            "high_risk_medications" IN risk_drivers:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             interventions.ADD("pharmacist_med_reconciliation")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF "admissions_past_6mo" IN risk_drivers:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             interventions.ADD("care_transition_program_enrollment")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF discharge_info.primary_diagnosis IN CHF_CODES:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             interventions.ADD("remote_weight_monitoring")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF feature_vector.zip_deprivation_index > 8:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             interventions.ADD("social_work_assessment")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF risk_tier == "MEDIUM":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         interventions.ADD("automated_check_in_call_day_7")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         interventions.ADD("ensure_followup_scheduled")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store the complete risk assessment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     risk_assessment = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id: discharge_info.patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         encounter_id: discharge_info.encounter_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         discharge_date: discharge_info.discharge_date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         probability: probability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         risk_tier: risk_tier,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         risk_drivers: risk_drivers,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         interventions: interventions,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model_version: score_result.model_version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         scored_at: score_result.scored_at,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ttl: discharge_info.discharge_date + 45 days  // Keep 15 days past window
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write to DynamoDB for downstream system access
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     DYNAMODB_PUT("readmission-risk-scores", risk_assessment)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Notify care team for high-risk patients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF risk_tier == "HIGH":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SNS_PUBLISH(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             topic = "high-risk-discharge-alerts",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             message = format_alert(risk_assessment),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             attributes = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "risk_tier": "HIGH",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "primary_diagnosis": discharge_info.primary_diagnosis,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "facility": discharge_info.facility_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN risk_assessment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 5: Outcome Tracking and Model Monitoring
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **What this does:** Monitors actual 30-day readmission outcomes against predictions, detects model drift, and triggers retraining when performance degrades.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **What goes wrong if you skip it:** Your model silently degrades over time as patient populations shift, coding practices change, or new care programs alter readmission patterns. Without monitoring, you won't know your predictions are wrong until someone manually audits them months later.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION track_outcomes_and_monitor():
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Run daily: check for readmissions among previously scored patients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     scored_patients = DYNAMODB_QUERY("readmission-risk-scores",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         discharge_date BETWEEN (today - 31 days) AND (today - 30 days))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each scored_patient IN scored_patients:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Check if patient was readmitted within 30 days
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         readmissions = FHIR_SEARCH("Encounter",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient = scored_patient.patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             type = "inpatient",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             date_range = [scored_patient.discharge_date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                          scored_patient.discharge_date + 30 days])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Exclude planned readmissions using CMS algorithm
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         unplanned = FILTER(readmissions, is_unplanned_readmission)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         actual_outcome = 1 IF COUNT(unplanned) > 0 ELSE 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Store outcome for model evaluation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         DYNAMODB_UPDATE("readmission-risk-scores",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             key = scored_patient.encounter_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             set actual_readmitted = actual_outcome,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             set outcome_date = NOW())
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Weekly: calculate model performance metrics
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     recent_scores = QUERY_LAST_30_DAYS_WITH_OUTCOMES()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     metrics = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         auc_roc: calculate_auc(recent_scores.probability, recent_scores.actual),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         calibration_slope: calculate_calibration(recent_scores),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         brier_score: calculate_brier(recent_scores),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         observed_rate_high_tier: rate(recent_scores WHERE tier="HIGH"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         observed_rate_low_tier: rate(recent_scores WHERE tier="LOW"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_scored: COUNT(recent_scores),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_readmitted: SUM(recent_scores.actual)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Publish metrics to CloudWatch
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     CLOUDWATCH_PUT_METRICS("ReadmissionModel", metrics)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Alert if performance degrades
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF metrics.auc_roc < 0.65 OR metrics.calibration_slope < 0.8:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SNS_PUBLISH("model-performance-alerts",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "Readmission model performance degraded. AUC: {metrics.auc_roc}. "
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "Consider retraining.")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN metrics
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter07.05-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
